# Best Practice Details

## Description
The Contribution Ladder establishes defined progression stages with increasing levels of trust, responsibility, operational ownership, and governance influence. :contentReference[oaicite:6]{index=6}

The framework defines four primary contributor stages:

| Stage | Description |
|---|---|
| New Contributor | Initial ecosystem participant learning tools, workflows, and contribution processes |
| Committer | Contributor with consistent, reliable contributions and growing project responsibility |
| Trusted Committer | Contributor trusted with broader operational responsibilities and mentorship |
| Core Maintainer | Senior ecosystem steward responsible for strategic direction, governance alignment, and project sustainability |

The framework emphasizes:
- Transparency
- Mentorship
- Continuous learning
- Community collaboration
- Sustainable stewardship
- Recognition and accountability

---

## Implementation Approach

### 1. Structured Onboarding
New contributors enter through a guided onboarding process introducing:
- Ecosystem culture
- Contribution workflows
- Documentation standards
- Governance expectations
- Initial beginner-friendly tasks

The framework recommends pairing contributors with mentors or developer advocates where possible. :contentReference[oaicite:7]{index=7}

---

### 2. Clear Advancement Criteria
Advancement between stages is based on measurable contribution and ecosystem participation metrics such as:
- Contribution consistency
- Time in role
- Peer review quality
- Community participation
- Operational reliability
- Mentorship participation
- Governance engagement

Transitions are evaluated by higher-trust contributors such as Trusted Committers or Core Maintainers. :contentReference[oaicite:8]{index=8}

---

### 3. Mentorship & Support Structures
The framework strongly emphasizes mentorship through:
- Contributor pairing
- Community support
- Workshops
- Webinars
- Documentation
- Meetups
- Knowledge-sharing events

The objective is to reduce onboarding complexity while improving contributor retention and confidence. :contentReference[oaicite:9]{index=9}

---

### 4. Recognition & Reward Systems
The framework includes structured recognition systems including:
- Public contributor recognition
- Digital badges
- Certificates
- Community visibility
- Leadership opportunities
- Governance participation
- Event access
- Expanded operational authority

The model recognizes that contributor retention depends not only on compensation but also on visibility, trust, and social recognition. :contentReference[oaicite:10]{index=10}

---

### 5. Adaptability Across Projects
The framework is intentionally adaptable to different project needs across the Cardano ecosystem.

Projects may customize:
- Advancement criteria
- Operational structures
- Mentorship systems
- Contributor requirements
- Governance processes

Intersect-affiliated projects are encouraged to document and report adaptations back to the OSC for ecosystem consistency and transparency. :contentReference[oaicite:11]{index=11}

